Rent and income in Barcelona: and unequal relationship¶

Berta Olivier Cañadell¶

To gather data about rent prices in Barcelona in the last four years and the income per capita I used the datasets provided by Barcelona's City Hall Open Data Service: https://opendataajuntament.barcelona.cat/data/en/organization/habitatge

I also briefly examined the data published by 'Idealista', which shows the top 50 most expensive cities in Spain: https://www.idealista.com/news/inmobiliario/vivienda/2023/10/13/808405-de-la-barceloneta-a-cuzco-los-50-barrios-mas-caros-para-alquilar-casa-en-espana. It is worth noting that this company gathers data by compiling information from advertisers' listed asking prices, so its data doesn't provide an accurate representation of the real prices. However they help draw the current tendencies in the housing market.

Now I will start working on the other datasets to start doing some comparisons between income and rent. Note that in each dataset there is a column for districts and a column for neighbourhoods. Barcelona is divided in 10 districts and each district has different neighbourhoods. The total number of neighbourhoods is 73. The datasets usually contain information specific to each neighbourhood and we can always see in which district each neighbourhood belongs.

In the dataset above we can see that each neighbourhood is repeated many times. This is because the dataset gives information about the income of each census sections. To try to make this a bit more simple we will merge the rows with the same neighbourhood name to end up with the average income for each neighbourhood.

In [38]:
#Merge the dataset
result_incomeB = incomeB.groupby('Neighbourhood')['Income'].mean().reset_index()
#We want to get a result of the income with only two decimals
result_incomeB['Income'] = result_incomeB['Income'].round(2)

Now I will try to make a visualization of the average income of each neighbourhood to see the differences between each more clearly. The library Matplotlib will allow me to do this visualization. When trying to plot the 73 neighbourhoods, the names in the x-axis did not fit and overlapped so it was not possible to read them. Therefore I decided to do a plot that only contains the neighbouhoods with a monthly income below 1.500€.

In [42]:
#We filter and choose those which have an income <1500. We will also add a title to the plot
filtered_result_incomeB = result_incomeB[result_incomeB['Monthly Income'] < 1500]
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8)) 
ax = filtered_result_incomeB.plot(kind='bar', x='Neighbourhood', y='Monthly Income', legend=False)
ax.set_xticks(ax.get_xticks())
ax.set_xticklabels(filtered_result_incomeB['Neighbourhood'], rotation=45, ha='right')
ax.set_title('Neighborhoods in Barcelona with a monthly income below 1500€')
ax.width = 1000 
plt.show()
#we import the plot
plt.savefig ('myplot.png')

We want to create a visualization but taking into account that each year in the df is divided into terms this can complicate our line graph. To simplify the df in order to get a line graph, we can calculate the average of €/m2 of each year.

In [181]:
#I convert the '€/m2' column to numeric
pricem2_barceloneta['€/m2'] = pd.to_numeric(pricem2_barceloneta['€/m2'], errors='coerce')

#I use the group by command and calculate the average for each year
pricem2_barceloneta = pricem2_barceloneta.groupby('Year')['€/m2'].mean().reset_index().round(2) #to make sure there are only 2 decimals

Additional memo¶

Besides gathering and analyzing this data I interviewed some experts to try to get a broader explanation of the situation. They pointed out that the Spanish law that aims to regulate and limit the rent prices in densely populated cities, like Barcelona, are not really working as it doesn't regulate temporary rentals, which are becoming more attractive for owners to avoid the law. They also pointed out to the lack of housing and especially of social housing in the city.
